{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15991"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.12,0.72,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63441"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8682"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48894"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20781"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63441"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the amniotic cavity expands and eventually comes into contact with the chorion. This process occurs around the second week after fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of the amniochorionic membrane?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Derives entirely from extraembryonic mesoderm","Develops from the yolk sac endoderm","Results from fusion of amnion and chorion","Forms by splitting of the primitive endoderm","Forms from fusion of amnion and allantois"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efusion of the amnion and chorion\u003C/strong\u003E creates the amniochorionic membrane, which forms the outer boundary of the amniotic cavity. This fusion occurs as the amniotic cavity expands during early development.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efusion of amnion and allantois\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur - the allantois develops as a separate structure from the yolk sac\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe membrane does not \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelop from yolk sac endoderm\u003C/strong\u003E - it is derived from amniotic ectoderm and chorionic tissues\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt does not \u003Cstrong\u003Ederive entirely from extraembryonic mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E - it includes both ectodermal and mesodermal components\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplitting of the primitive endoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the yolk sac, not the amniochorionic membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe amniochorionic membrane is a complex structure consisting of amniotic epithelium, basement membrane, and connective tissue derived from the chorion. It plays an important role in maintaining the amniotic fluid environment around the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The amniochorionic membrane forms when the expanding amnion fuses with the chorion during early embryonic development.","The amniochorionic membrane consists of amniotic epithelium, basement membrane, and connective tissue derived from the chorion."],"references":["Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48894"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48894"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T22:49:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T22:49:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8682"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63441"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0